title: Known for Feuding With Immigrants, a TV Star Wants to Run a Town Many Call Home
content: A mayoral bid by a TV commentator known for her inflammatory messaging on race raises a larger question: How should Portugal address its colonial legacy?

title: Labour’s Leader Struggles to Emerge From Boris Johnson’s Shadow
content: Competent but low on charisma, Keir Starmer has yet to give British voters a clear reason to support the main opposition party, critics say.

title: Five Years After Peace Deal, Colombia Is Running Out of Time, Experts Say
content: A treaty with rebels in 2016 called for the end of a decades-long war. But that is not same as achieving peace, and the window for doing so may be closing.

title: U.K.’s Migrant Boat Dispute Has Eyes Fixed on the Channel
content: The southeastern coast of England is increasingly the focal point of Britain’s migration debate as the government advocates more extreme measures to halt asylum seekers arriving by boat.

title: In Reversal, Israel’s New Government Engages With Palestinian Authority
content: The government has held high-level meetings with Palestinian officials and aided the Palestinians economically, a sharp change from the previous government.

title: North Korea Dangles Hopes for Summit and End-of-War Declaration
content: Kim Jong-un’s sister responds to the South Korean leader’s last attempt to put the peace process back on track, but skepticism abounds.

title: A Nervy Trip to Kabul: How Ukraine Negotiated With the Taliban and Rescued 96 Afghans
content: Few countries have been willing to fly rescue missions into Afghanistan since the Americans left. Ukraine is an exception. It says it has a different definition of danger.

title: For India’s Military, a Juggling Act on Two Hostile Fronts
content: Tensions with China and Pakistan stretch a cash-starved military, while the fall of Afghanistan to the Taliban removes a potential ally.

title: To Get Back Arrested Executive, China Uses a Hardball Tactic: Seizing Foreigners
content: The speed at which Beijing returned two Canadians held seemingly tit-for-tat in exchange may signal comfort with the tactic.

title: Can Macron Lead the European Union After Merkel Retires?
content: Emmanuel Macron, the French president, would love to fill the German chancellor’s shoes. But a Europe with no single, central figure may be more likely.

title: Rebuking Biden, Iran’s Chief Diplomat Demands More Sanctions Relief
content: The foreign minister for Iran’s new hard-line government said it would demand a higher price for limiting its nuclear program than it did in the 2015 deal.

title: Europe Tightens Purse Strings to Try to Pressure Poland and Hungary
content: Frustrations over rule of law violations in the two countries have prompted the European Union to block payments in an effort to bolster legal action.

title: An Insider Details the ‘Black Box’ of Money and Power in China
content: A memoir by a well-connected businessman offers insights into the Communist Party’s thinking as it tightens its grip on the private sector.

title: South Korea will start giving vaccine boosters amid a surge in Covid cases.
content: The country has seen a spike in infections after Chuseok, a three-day holiday celebrating the fall harvest.

title: Swiss Voters Approve Law Allowing Same-Sex Marriages
content: The legislation, endorsed in a referendum, will also allow same-sex couples to use sperm banks and to adopt children for the first time.

title: What to watch for on Sunday.
content: Sixty million people are eligible to vote in the German national election on Sunday.

title: Women Enslaved by ISIS Say They Did Not Consent to a Film About Them
content: The acclaimed documentary “Sabaya” portrays the rescue of Yazidi women sexually enslaved by the Islamic State terrorist group. But many of the traumatized women said they never agreed to be in the film.

title: New York weighs using the National Guard to replace unvaccinated health care workers.
content: Gov. Kathy Hochul has plans to use National Guard members and out-of-state professionals to cover staff shortages if thousands of health care workers fail to meet a state vaccination deadline on Monday.

title: Icelanders Vote in Volatile Election With Climate in Mind
content: Icelanders voted Saturday in a general election dominated by climate change, with an unprecedented number of political parties likely to win parliamentary seats.

title: Norway lifts coronavirus restrictions after 561 days.
content: “Now the time has come to return to a normal daily life,” the prime minister, Erna Solberg, said.

title: How Record Rain and Officials’ Mistakes Led to Drownings on a Subway
content: The deluge in the city of Zhengzhou revealed how China’s years of go-go construction had left its cities vulnerable to climate change.

title: A federal appeals court delays New York City’s vaccine mandate for teachers.
content: The mandate, which affects well over 150,000 people working in the nation’s largest school system, was set to go into effect on Monday at midnight.

title: Pfizer boosters are recommended for many Americans, and Alaska faces its worst surge: The week in Covid news.
Affluent, Anxious and Almost Normal: A Journey Through Merkel’s Germany
content: As Germany heads into an election that will see Angela Merkel step down after 16 years as chancellor, she leaves behind a country profoundly changed — and anxious about changing more.

title: Whales So Close You Can Touch Them: A Family Adventure in Canada
content: Recalling a prepandemic trip to a watery landscape in Quebec province: “The adventure we had feels like one plucked from a world I can no longer reach, not unlike watching the water, waiting for a whale to crest.”

title: Wole Soyinka Is Not Going Anywhere
content: The Nobel laureate, whose new novel, “Chronicles From the Land of the Happiest People on Earth,” is his first in nearly 50 years, refuses to back down when he senses that his homeland’s freedom is under threat.

title: China frees 2 jailed Canadians after the U.S. agrees to release a Huawei executive.
content: Two Canadians imprisoned in China since 2018 were free and on their way home, Prime Minister Justin Trudeau of Canada announced on Friday night.

title: Alberta’s ‘Best Summer Ever’ Ends With an Overwhelmed Medical System
content: A surge of Covid-19 cases has forced the province to ask for military assistance in airlifting patients to hospitals across the country.

title: Canadians weigh in on the Meng deal: ‘What about the two Michaels?’
Pakistan Says U.N. Envoy of Old Afghan Government Should Vacate Seat
content: Stopping short of urging that a Taliban envoy to the U.N. be accepted, Pakistan’s foreign minister suggested that stability had improved in Taliban-ruled Afghanistan.

title: In Britain, Rising Prices and Shortages Evoke 1970s-Style Jitters
content: The nation’s economy is very different from the bleak days of the 70s, but certain parallels are unnerving Britons and loom as a potential headache for Prime Minister Boris Johnson.

title: Who are the Canadians detained after Ms. Meng’s arrest?
Meng’s release could eliminate a source of friction between China and the Biden administration.
content: Since coming to office, President Biden has taken a tough position on China but has also sought common ground.

title: Ahead of German Election, Hundreds of Thousands Demand Climate Action
content: Protests took place worldwide, but those in Germany had heightened urgency amid calls for the next government to do something about climate change.
